<p>Pretty self explanatory, you set a div’s id to equal “post-text” then passing that in on the js side to take on whatever value the slider is at. The colors I chose fit my client’s site, but any would do if you were to implement this. I created the “arrow” or triangle by using border left, top and right on the “thumb”. It is important to code for both moz (mozilla) and webkit (chrome, safari). Check out the demo below:</p>

<div class="slidecontainer">
<p>Text Size: <span id="size"></span></p>  
<input type="range" min="19" max="40" value="19" class="slider" id="font-range" />
 </div>

<script>
  var slider = document.getElementById("font-range");
  var output = document.getElementById("size");
  output.innerHTML = slider.value;  
  slider.oninput = function() {
  output.innerHTML = this.value;
  document.getElementById("post-text").style.fontSize = output.innerHTML;}
</script>

<p>   </p>
<div id="post-text">Hi, this text will change size!</div>

